y of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: unexplained.","German: possibly a variant of   Pech   ‘pitch, tar’.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Peče</b> or of its Germanized form   Petsche  , which is also a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Pech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Manuel, Alvaro, Diego, Edelmira, Emilio, Francisco, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose Angel.  German Gerhard, Hans, Ilse, Lutz, Manfred, Wolf.","Czech and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":32,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Nicholas Peche was born in 1183, in Kettlebaston, Suffolk, England as the son of Sir Ralph de Peche. He married Alice Sifrewast about 1206, in Boylestone, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1216, in Frilsham, Berkshire, England, at the age of 33, and was buried in Priory, County Kilkenny, Ireland."},"et":{"1183–1216":"1183–1216","1191–1242":"1191–1242","–Male":"Surnud","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1208–1283":"1208–1283","1162–1173":"1162–1173","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1242":"1242","1173":"1173","1162":"1162","1283":"1283","1184":"1184","1183":"1183","1208":"1208","Abt 1206":"umbes 1206","1191":"1191","Dunstaple Priory,":"Priory, County Kilkenny, Iirimaa","Frilsham, Berkshire, England":"Frilsham, Berkshire, England","Kettlebaston, Suffolk, England":"Kettlebaston, Suffolk, England","of Boylestone, Derby, England":"Boylestone, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Boylestone, Derbyshire, England":"Boylestone, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1183–1216":"1183–1216","1191–1242":"1191–1242","–Male":"Kuollut","118